  "text": "## Kafka Log Compaction Architecture\n\nApache Kafka's log compaction feature is implemented across multiple Java source files in the `storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/` directory. The architecture consists of three main components:\n\n### 1. The Cleaner Thread Implementation\n\nThe **LogCleaner.java** file serves as the main coordinator for log compaction. It implements `BrokerReconfigurable` and manages a pool of background cleaner threads. The key inner class is **CleanerThread**, which extends `ShutdownableThread` and implements the thread that performs the actual cleaning work.\n\nThe cleaning lifecycle in LogCleaner.cleanFilthiestLog() follows this sequence:\n1. Uses LogCleanerManager.grabFilthiestCompactedLog() to select the log with the highest ratio of dirty bytes to total bytes\n2. Builds an offset map for the dirty section using Cleaner.buildOffsetMap()\n3. Cleans the segments using Cleaner.cleanSegments()\n4. Replaces the old segments with cleaned ones\n\n### 2. Segment Selection Policy\n\nThe **LogCleanerManager.java** file implements the segment selection policy. Key methods include:\n\n- **grabFilthiestCompactedLog()** - Selects the log with the highest cleanable ratio (dirtiest log), implementing the policy of choosing logs that benefit most from cleaning\n- **calculateCleanableBytes()** - Computes the number of cleanable bytes between the first dirty offset and the first uncleanable offset\n\nThe **LogToClean.java** class represents a log selected for cleaning and compares logs by their `cleanableRatio`, which is calculated as `cleanableBytes / totalBytes`. This ratio determines which log is \"filthiest\" and should be cleaned next.\n\n### 3. Key-Based Deduplication Logic\n\nThe deduplication logic uses two key classes:\n\n- **OffsetMap.java** (interface) - Defines the contract for the deduplication map with methods: put(), get(), updateLatestOffset(), clear(), size(), slots(), and latestOffset()\n\n- **SkimpyOffsetMap.java** (implementation) - Implements the actual deduplication map using a cryptographically secure hash (MD5 by default) to map keys to their latest offsets. It uses:\n  - Hash table with collision resolution via probing\n  - MessageDigest for hashing keys to save memory overhead\n  - No delete support (only put and get operations)\n  - Configurable hash algorithms (MD2, MD5, SHA-1, SHA-256, SHA-384, SHA-512)\n\nThe **Cleaner.java** class contains the core deduplication logic:\n\n- **buildOffsetMap()** - Builds the key=>offset mapping for the dirty section of the log by reading messages and storing the latest offset for each key\n- **buildOffsetMapForSegment()** - Processes individual segments to populate the offset map\n- **cleanSegments()** - Uses the offset map to deduplicate: for each message in a segment, it checks if a newer message with the same key exists in the offset map (in the head/dirty portion). If so, the message is discarded; otherwise, it's retained in the cleaned segment\n\n### Supporting Components\n\n- **CleanerConfig.java** - Provides configuration parameters for the cleaner (buffer size, thread count, I/O rates, etc.)\n- **CleanerStats.java** - Collects cleaning statistics (bytes read/written, messages processed, timing info)\n- **PreCleanStats.java** - Collects pre-cleaning statistics (max compaction delays, cleanable partitions count)\n- **CleanedTransactionMetadata.java** - Handles transaction state during cleaning, manages aborted transactions and control markers\n- **LogCleaningException.java** and **LogCleaningAbortedException.java** - Handle cleaning-related errors\n- **LogCleaningState.java** - Tracks the state of each partition being cleaned (None, InProgress, Aborted, Paused)\n\nThe architecture efficiently implements log compaction by separating concerns: the LogCleanerManager handles selection policy, Cleaner handles the actual deduplication using the OffsetMap for efficient key lookup, and CleanerThread manages the execution lifecycle."
}

